    "code": "import sys\nfrom collections import deque\ninput = sys.stdin.readline\n\ndef solve():\n    n, m = map(int, input().split())\n    grid = []\n    lab = None\n    for i in range(n):\n        row = list(input().strip())\n        grid.append(row)\n        for j in range(len(row)):\n            if row[j] == 'L':\n                lab = (i, j)\n    \n    # A cell is \"good\" if the robot can be forced to reach the lab from it.\n    # Key insight: a free cell is good if the number of free neighbors minus 1 <= \n    # the number of good neighbors. In other words, a cell is good if it has at most 1\n    # free neighbor that is not good (because we can command the robot to go in any direction\n    # except toward that non-good neighbor, forcing it to go to a good neighbor).\n    # \n    # More precisely: a free cell can be forced if the number of free neighbors that are NOT good\n    # is <= 1. Because if there's at most 1 bad free neighbor, we command the robot to move\n    # toward that bad neighbor, so the robot must choose a different direction, and all other\n    # free neighbors are good.\n    # Wait, let me reconsider.\n    # \n    # The robot moves in any direction EXCEPT the commanded one, as long as that direction is free.\n    # We want: no matter what the robot chooses (from the available directions != commanded), it ends up good.\n    # So we need: for some command direction d, all free neighbors except possibly the one in direction d are good.\n    # Equivalently: the number of free neighbors that are NOT good is <= 1.\n    # (If 0 bad free neighbors: any command works)\n    # (If 1 bad free neighbor: command the robot to go toward that bad neighbor, robot must go elsewhere, all good)\n    # (If 2+ bad free neighbors: no command can prevent robot from going to a bad neighbor)\n    # \n    # BFS from lab, adding cells when their count of non-good free neighbors drops to <= 1.\n    \n    dirs = [(-1,0),(1,0),(0,-1),(0,1)]\n    \n    # Count free neighbors for each cell\n    free_neighbors = [[0]*m for _ in range(n)]\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(m):\n            if grid[i][j] == '#':\n                continue\n            cnt = 0\n            for di, dj in dirs:\n                ni, nj = i+di, j+dj\n                if 0 <= ni < n and 0 <= nj < m and grid[ni][nj] != '#':\n                    cnt += 1\n            free_neighbors[i][j] = cnt\n    \n    good = [[False]*m for _ in range(n)]\n    # bad_free_neighbors[i][j] = number of free neighbors of (i,j) that are not yet good\n    bad_free = [row[:] for row in free_neighbors]\n    \n    queue = deque()\n    # Lab is always good\n    li, lj = lab\n    good[li][lj] = True\n    queue.append((li, lj))\n    \n    # When a cell becomes good, update its neighbors\n    while queue:\n        r, c = queue.popleft()\n        for dr, dc in dirs:\n            nr, nc = r+dr, c+dc\n            if 0 <= nr < n and 0 <= nc < m and grid[nr][nc] != '#' and not good[nr][nc]:\n                bad_free[nr][nc] -= 1\n                if bad_free[nr][nc] <= 1:\n                    good[nr][nc] = True\n                    queue.append((nr, nc))\n    \n    result = []\n    for i in range(n):\n        row = []\n        for j in range(m):\n            if grid[i][j] == '.' and good[i][j]:\n                row.append('+')\n            else:\n                row.append(grid[i][j])\n        result.append(''.join(row))\n    print('\\n'.join(result))\n\nt = int(input())\nfor _ in range(t):\n    solve()",
